		<section>
			<h2 id="what">What are Quokkas</h2>
			<p>
				Quokkas are the happiest animal in Australia that surprisngly
				isn't trying to kill you. They're Australian marsupials (related
				to kangaroos and wallabies), only found on a small island called
				Rottnest Island, off the coast of Perth. They're herbivores
				(although will eat most food you leave lying around) and have no
				natural predators therefore aren't afraid of humans.
			</p>
			<!-- <img src="/img/rottnest.jpg" alt="Rottnest Island" /> -->
			<figure>
				<picture>
					<source srcset="/img/rottnest.webp" type="image/webp" />
					<source
						srcset="/img/rottnest-500_x_375.jpg"
						media="(min-width: 700px)"
					/>
					<source
						srcset="/img/rottnest-300_x_224.jpg"
						media="(min-width: 500px)"
					/>
					<img src="/img/rottnest.jpg" alt="" />
				</picture>
			</figure>
			<p>
				But what Quokkas are most known for, is the fact that they look
				like they're smiling and their penchant for selfies. Quokkas
				have a happy, genial expression which is actually due to
				evolution. Like canines, Quokkas' mouths open slightly to pant
				allowing them to cool themselves. When they're happy and hot
				(which is quite often, especially this last few months), they
				seem like they are smiling.
			</p>
			<figure>
				<img src="/img/quokka_2.jpg" alt="" />
				<figcaption>This is a Quokka</figcaption>
			</figure>
			<p>
				Although tourists and visitors to the island love Quokkas, the
				locals don't appreciate them as much. Due to their lack of fear
				for humans, Quokkas will regularly enter buildings such as homes
				or restaurants.
			</p>
			<img src="/img/quokka_3.jpg" />
			<img src="/img/quokka_1.jpg" />

