			<h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Quokkas</h2>
			<details>
				<summary>Are Quokkas real?</summary>
				<div>
					<p>
						Is Australia real? Are we even real? What is real? Are
						we all just a figment of someone's imagination? Or part
						of the matrix?
					</p>
					<p>
						Yes, Quokkas are real. They seem too good to be true,
						and a bit too weird (like most animals in Australia, I'm
						still convinced that platypus' are a myth), but they do
						genuinely exist.
					</p>
				</div>
			</details>
			<details>
				<summary>Can I have one?</summary>
				<p>
					Quokkas are only native to one island in Australia, and
					don't do well outside of their natural habitat. They're not
					great as pets, it would be similar to keeping a squirrel as
					a pet.
				</p>
			</details>
			<details>
				<summary>What threatens Quokkas?</summary>
				<p>
					Although mainland Quokkas are threatened by the European red
					fox, domesticated cats and dogs as well as wild birds of
					prey and dingoes, Rottnest Island (where most Quokkas live),
					is free of most of these predators.
				</p>
			</details>
			<details>
				<summary>What happens if I try and steal a Quokka?</summary>
				<p>
					Rottnest Island Authority can issue a $100 fine for picking
					up a Quokka, and you can be taken to court and subject to a
					fine of up to $1000.
				</p>
			</details>
			<details>
				<summary>What does a Quokka do when threatened?</summary>
				<p>
					If a Quokka mother is threatened by a predator, she will
					often throw her baby on the ground to distract the predator
					and save her own life.
				</p>
				<img src="/img/quokka_6.jpg" />
			</details>
			<details>
				<summary>How do I pronounce "Quokka"?</summary>
				<p>Quokka is pronounced <em>kwaa-ka</em></p>
				<p>
					The name Quokka comes from the Aboriginal people that lived
					in Western Australia where they were first discovered.
				</p>
			</details>
